<!-- SECTION 1 -->
<h1>1. Blood Pressure Staging &amp; Hypertensive Crisis</h1>

<h2>ACC/AHA 2017 BP Categories</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Category</th><th>Systolic</th><th>Diastolic</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Normal</td><td>&lt; 120 mmHg</td><td>&lt; 80 mmHg</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Elevated</td><td>120–129 mmHg</td><td>&lt; 80 mmHg</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Stage 1</td><td>130–139 mmHg</td><td>80–89 mmHg (one or both)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Stage 2</td><td>≥ 140 mmHg</td><td>≥ 90 mmHg (one or both)</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Hypertensive Crisis</strong></td><td><strong>&gt; 180 mmHg (and/or)</strong></td><td><strong>≥ 120 mmHg</strong></td></tr>
</table>

<div class="box box-yellow">⚡ STAGING RULE: Always stage by the NUMBER MOST OUT OF RANGE.<br>Example: BP 120/90 → Diastolic 90 drives the stage → Stage 2, not Normal.</div>

<h2>Hypertensive Crisis — Clinical Decision Making</h2>
<ul>
  <li>BP at crisis level does <strong>NOT</strong> automatically mean ambulance</li>
  <li>Some patients chronically run at crisis-level BP — their body has adapted to long-standing uncontrolled HTN</li>
  <li>Still carries HIGH risk for stroke and cardiac events</li>
</ul>
<table>
  <tr><th>Scenario</th><th>Action Required</th></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Crisis BP + chest pain / stroke sx / SOB</strong></td><td class="emer">AMBULANCE NOW — Emergency Department immediately</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Crisis BP + disc edema + <strong>NO systemic sx</strong></td><td class="urg">URGENT — urgent care within 24–48h; NOT ambulance</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Crisis BP + no eye findings + no sx</td><td>Urgent medical management within the week</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="box box-red">🚨 DECISION POINT: SYMPTOMS of acute end-organ damage decide ER vs urgent referral — NOT the BP number alone.</div>

<h2>Hypertensive Retinopathy — Stages</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Stage</th><th>Findings</th></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Stage 1</strong></td><td>Arteriolar attenuation + increased light reflex (copper/silver wiring)</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Stage 2</strong></td><td>Stage 1 + AV crossing changes (AV nicking)</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Stage 3</strong></td><td>Stages 1+2 + hemorrhages + cotton wool spots (CWS)</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Stage 4</strong></td><td><span class="emer">DISC EDEMA</span> = Stages 1–3 + disc edema = Hypertensive Crisis / End-Organ Damage</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="box box-yellow">⚡ EXAM ANCHOR: Stage 4 = Disc Edema = End-Organ Damage = Hypertensive Crisis.<br>Disc edema from HTN is the most urgency-defining eye finding in this module.</div>

<h2>Case 1 Anchor — Boards-Style</h2>
<ul>
  <li>50-year-old male; no medical care since 2017; last BP 240/140; never took prescribed lisinopril</li>
  <li>Presents to optometry: central blur OD ×2 weeks; VA 20/400 OD / 20/25 OS; normal anterior segment</li>
  <li>In-office BP: <strong>292/162</strong> — highest the instructor has seen in clinic</li>
  <li>Patient calm, no chest pain, no stroke sx, no SOB → long-standing adaptation</li>
  <li>Management: urgent care + pharmacy within 48h + retina referral for macular edema; <strong>NOT ambulance</strong></li>
</ul>
<div class="box box-blue">🧠 MNEMONIC: Central blur + VA drop + chronic HTN history → think POSTERIOR SEGMENT (disc/macula), NOT anterior segment.</div>

<!-- SECTION 2 -->
<h1>2. Retinal Vein Occlusions (BRVO &amp; CRVO)</h1>

<h2>Pathophysiology</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Chronic HTN → arteriosclerosis → arteries harden, narrow, increase light reflex</li>
  <li>AV nicking: hardened artery crosses over vein → compresses it → venous collapse</li>
  <li>Sudden hemorrhage into retina → "Blood and Thunder" appearance in CRVO</li>
</ul>
<div class="box box-green">✅ VISUAL RULE: Vein Occlusion = BLOOD (hemorrhagic) + THROMBUS<br>Artery Occlusion = WHITE (infarcted) + EMBOLUS</div>

<h2>Types &amp; Risk Factors</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>CRVO:</strong> entire retina affected; Blood and Thunder appearance</li>
  <li><strong>BRVO:</strong> sector of retina; artery compresses branch vein</li>
  <li><strong>Risk factors:</strong> Age, HTN, Diabetes, Vasculopathy, Obesity, Coagulation disorders, Smoking</li>
</ul>

<h2>Management</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Take BP in office; communicate with PCP for BP and risk factor management</li>
  <li>Often self-resolves over months</li>
  <li>Macular edema → retina referral + Anti-VEGF injections</li>
  <li><strong>NOT an emergency</strong> — never send to ER for vein occlusion alone</li>
</ul>
<div class="box box-yellow">⚡ MNEMONIC: Vein problem = Bleeding + Time + PCP. NEVER an emergency.</div>

<!-- SECTION 3 -->
<h1>3. Plaques &amp; Artery Occlusions</h1>

<h2>Hollenhorst Plaque</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Shiny, hyper-reflective <strong>cholesterol embolus INSIDE an artery</strong> (usually at bifurcation)</li>
  <li>Most commonly originates from <strong>CAROTID ARTERIES</strong></li>
  <li>Best seen on: Infrared imaging, OCT; also visible clinically</li>
  <li>Must be <em>inside</em> the artery to qualify as Hollenhorst</li>
</ul>
<div class="box box-blue">🧠 MNEMONIC: Shiny + Inside artery + Bifurcation = Hollenhorst. A sparkling cholesterol crystal stuck at a fork in the road.</div>

<h2>Plaque Types (Course Focus = Hollenhorst)</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Type</th><th>Origin</th><th>Size/Danger</th><th>Course Emphasis</th></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Hollenhorst</strong></td><td>Carotid artery (most common)</td><td>Smaller; very shiny</td><td><span class="emer">PRIMARY FOCUS for this course</span></td></tr>
  <tr><td>Calcific</td><td>Cardiac origin</td><td>Larger, more dangerous</td><td>Covered more in AOD</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Platelet-Fibrin</td><td>Cardiac origin</td><td>Larger, more dangerous</td><td>Covered more in AOD</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>Asymptomatic vs. Symptomatic Plaque — CRITICAL DISTINCTION</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Type</th><th>Presentation</th><th>Urgency</th><th>Management</th></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Asymptomatic</strong></td><td>Found incidentally; no vision event</td><td class="urg">URGENT outpatient (NOT ER)</td><td>Carotid Doppler; PCP; aspirin/anticoagulation; within 2 weeks</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Symptomatic (TMVL)</strong></td><td>Curtain/shade vision loss that resolves as embolus moves</td><td class="emer">EMERGENCY (stroke protocol)</td><td>Immediate ER; emergent stroke workup; screen for neurologic sx</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="box box-red">🚨 ABSOLUTE RULE: Curtain vision loss (TMVL) = STROKE = ER NOW.<br>Ask about: numbness, weakness, tingling, trouble speaking/swallowing, double vision.</div>

<h2>Retinal Artery Occlusion (BRAO / CRAO)</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Plaque lodges and blocks flow → artery occlusion → downstream retina loses oxygen</li>
  <li>Appearance: diffuse retinal <strong>WHITENING</strong> + cherry red spot (CRAO) or sector whitening (BRAO)</li>
  <li>Think of it as a giant cotton wool spot — RNFL swells from ischemia</li>
  <li>OCT shows very swollen (thickened) retina from cellular ischemia (oxygen loss → cellular dysfunction → swelling)</li>
</ul>
<div class="box box-red">🚨 ARTERY OCCLUSION = STROKE EQUIVALENT = ER IMMEDIATELY<br>Stroke workup within 24 hours. If patient &gt;50: ALWAYS rule out Giant Cell Arteritis (GCA).</div>

<h2>Urgency Ladder Summary</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Condition</th><th>Urgency</th><th>Timeline</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Artery occlusion (BRAO/CRAO)</td><td class="emer">EMERGENCY</td><td>Immediate ER; stroke workup within 24h</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Transient Monocular Vision Loss (TMVL)</td><td class="emer">EMERGENCY</td><td>Immediate ER; treat like stroke</td></tr>
  <tr><td>HTN crisis + systemic sx (chest pain, SOB, stroke sx)</td><td class="emer">EMERGENCY (ambulance)</td><td>Call 911 now</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Asymptomatic Hollenhorst plaque</td><td class="urg">URGENT (not ER)</td><td>Carotid study + PCP within 2 weeks</td></tr>
  <tr><td>HTN crisis + disc edema + NO systemic sx</td><td class="urg">URGENT (not ER)</td><td>Urgent care within 24–48h</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Vein occlusion (BRVO/CRVO)</td><td class="safe">NOT emergency</td><td>PCP + BP; retina if macular edema</td></tr>
</table>

<!-- SECTION 4 -->
<h1>4. Anticoagulation &amp; Retinal Bleeding</h1>

<h2>The Common Patient Question</h2>
<p>Patients on anticoagulants (aspirin, Eliquis, Warfarin, Plavix) ask: <em>"Will my blood thinner increase retinal bleeding or convert my dry AMD to wet AMD?"</em></p>

<h2>The Answer</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>CONTINUE anticoagulants</strong> — do NOT advise stopping them because of retinal bleeding concerns</li>
  <li><strong>AREDS-2 study:</strong> showed NO increased risk of progression to exudative (wet) AMD with daily aspirin or anticoagulants</li>
  <li>Stroke/cardiac risk from stopping anticoagulation OUTWEIGHS any retinal bleeding concern</li>
</ul>
<div class="box box-yellow">⚡ EXAM RULE: Patient on ASA/anticoagulants + AMD → CONTINUE the medication.<br>If question asks: "Should patient stop aspirin because AMD might bleed?" → Answer: NO.</div>

<!-- SECTION 5 -->
<h1>5. Phenylephrine Safety</h1>

<h2>2.5% vs. 10% Phenylephrine</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Concentration</th><th>Common Use</th><th>Risk Level</th><th>Clinical Rule</th></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>2.5%</strong></td><td>Routine dilation in outpatient clinic</td><td class="safe">VERY LOW — no significant BP or HR change</td><td>Use on ALL outpatients; safe for HTN, DM, CAD, asthma</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>10%</strong></td><td>Breaking synechiae; some clinics/states</td><td class="urg">LOW but real — can raise HR ~+15bpm</td><td>Caution in CV risk patients; monitor ~1 hour; may not be available in MA</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="box box-green">✅ MNEMONIC: 2.5% = Safe for all. 10% = Be careful. Never confuse the two on an exam.</div>

<h2>Common Questions Answered</h2>
<h3>Patient with hypertension — use phenylephrine?</h3>
<p>YES. 2.5% is safe. Study showed no significant BP or HR change within 20–60 minutes after instillation.</p>
<h3>Patient with CAD, 3 MIs, CABG, DM — use phenylephrine?</h3>
<p>YES. Comorbidities alone are NOT a contraindication. More important to see the retina, especially with DM.</p>
<h3>Patient with asthma — use phenylephrine?</h3>
<p>YES. Asthma is NOT a contraindication to phenylephrine. Asthma screening in clinic is for <strong>carbonic anhydrase inhibitors and glaucoma meds</strong> — not phenylephrine. Different drug class entirely.</p>
<h3>When would you possibly avoid phenylephrine?</h3>
<p>Very elderly or medically unstable <em>inpatient</em> scenarios (e.g., patient who just had open-heart surgery). In typical outpatient optometry clinic settings, 2.5% is always appropriate.</p>
<h3>Is tropicamide the same concern?</h3>
<p>NO. Tropicamide is an anticholinergic — completely different drug class. Tropicamide is always fine. Tropicamide cautions relate to Down syndrome, not cardiac/pulmonary risk.</p>
<div class="box box-yellow">⚡ EXAM ANCHOR: You will not kill your patient with 2.5% phenylephrine. In outpatient optometry = 2.5% always appropriate.</div>

