<h1>7. Mnemonics &amp; Memory Anchors</h1>
<table>
  <tr><th>Mnemonic</th><th>What It Helps You Remember</th></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>White = Artery, Blood = Vein</strong></td><td>Artery occlusion → white infarcted retina (embolus). Vein occlusion → hemorrhagic (thrombus).</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Curtain vision = Stroke = ER NOW</strong></td><td>Transient monocular vision loss that fades like a curtain = TMVL = treat like stroke.</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>2.5 = Safe, 10 = Careful</strong></td><td>2.5% phenylephrine safe for all outpatients. 10% can raise HR; use caution.</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Stage by the worst number</strong></td><td>Always grade HTN by the most abnormal value (systolic or diastolic).</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Disc edema = Stage 4 = Crisis</strong></td><td>Optic disc edema from HTN = end-organ damage = hypertensive crisis level.</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Shiny at bifurcation = Hollenhorst</strong></td><td>Bright shiny cholesterol embolus inside artery at bifurcation = Hollenhorst plaque.</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Symptoms decide the ambulance</strong></td><td>HTN crisis number alone ≠ ambulance. Systemic symptoms (chest pain, stroke sx) do.</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Vein = BP + PCP + Time</strong></td><td>Vein occlusion: control BP, PCP, may self-resolve. NEVER emergency.</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Artery = ER + Stroke + GCA</strong></td><td>Artery occlusion: immediate ER, stroke workup within 24h, rule out GCA if age >50.</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Continue the anticoagulant</strong></td><td>AMD + anticoagulants: do NOT stop meds. Stroke risk &gt; retinal bleeding risk (AREDS-2).</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Asthma questions are for CAIs</strong></td><td>Asthma screening = carbonic anhydrase inhibitors. NOT about phenylephrine safety.</td></tr>
</table>

