<!-- SECTION 9 -->
<h1>9. Practice Questions</h1>

<div class="q-block"><p>Q1. A 63-year-old woman has BP 185/122 and bilateral disc edema on fundus exam. She is calm, denies chest pain, SOB, and has no stroke symptoms. What is the most appropriate management?</p></div>
<div class="box box-green">Answer: URGENT but NOT ambulance. HTN crisis (BP ≥180/120) + disc edema = Stage 4 / end-organ damage. BUT no systemic symptoms = emergent timeline, not emergency department NOW. Management: urgent care within 24–48h; restart/optimize antihypertensives; retina referral for macular edema. Do NOT call ambulance based on BP and eye findings alone without systemic symptoms.</div>

<div class="q-block"><p>Q2. A 55-year-old male reports a curtain descending over his left eye vision for ~5 minutes, which fully resolved. He is now asymptomatic and fundus exam is normal. What do you do?</p></div>
<div class="box box-red">Answer: EMERGENCY — send to ER immediately. This is Transient Monocular Vision Loss (TMVL) = stroke symptom. Normal fundus does NOT change urgency — the embolus may have moved. Ask about neurologic symptoms (numbness, weakness, trouble speaking). Send to ER for emergent stroke workup. Also order carotid Doppler.</div>

<div class="q-block"><p>Q3. On routine exam of a 69-year-old with CAD, 3 MIs, HTN, HLD, and DM, you see a small shiny bright spot inside a retinal artery near a bifurcation OS. He is completely asymptomatic. What is the finding and management?</p></div>
<div class="box box-green">Answer: Asymptomatic Hollenhorst plaque. Shiny cholesterol embolus inside artery at bifurcation = Hollenhorst. Asymptomatic = URGENT outpatient, NOT ER. Management: communicate with PCP, carotid Doppler within 2 weeks, consider aspirin/anticoagulation, educate patient about TMVL warning signs and to seek ER care immediately if curtain vision occurs.</div>

<div class="q-block"><p>Q4. A patient with wet AMD asks if they should stop their low-dose aspirin (81mg daily) prescribed by their cardiologist for stroke prevention, worried it will worsen their macular bleeding. What do you tell them?</p></div>
<div class="box box-green">Answer: Continue the aspirin. AREDS-2 study showed NO increased risk of progression to exudative AMD with daily aspirin or anticoagulants. The stroke/cardiac risk of stopping anticoagulation FAR outweighs any retinal bleeding concern. Do NOT advise stopping anticoagulants due to fear of retinal bleeding from AMD.</div>

<div class="q-block"><p>Q5. You are about to dilate a 71-year-old patient with CAD, 4 CABG surgeries, 3 MIs, DM, HTN, and HLD. Should you use topical phenylephrine 2.5%?</p></div>
<div class="box box-green">Answer: YES. Use 2.5% phenylephrine. Comorbidities alone are NOT a contraindication. 2.5% causes no significant BP or HR change. Patients with DM and cardiac history dilate poorly — it is MORE important, not less, to achieve adequate dilation to examine the retina thoroughly.</div>

<div class="q-block"><p>Q6. A 59-year-old male has blurry vision OD ×2 weeks. BP is 155/82. Fundus shows flame hemorrhages and tortuous dilated veins in a wedge-shaped distribution. What is the diagnosis and management?</p></div>
<div class="box box-green">Answer: Branch Retinal Vein Occlusion (BRVO). HTN → arteriosclerosis → AV nicking → vein compressed → sector hemorrhage. Management: BP in office (done), communicate with PCP for BP and risk factor control, retina referral if macula involved (anti-VEGF may be needed). NOT an emergency. May self-resolve over months.</div>

<div class="q-block"><p>Q7. Which best distinguishes a retinal artery occlusion from a retinal vein occlusion on fundus exam? (A) Disc edema, (B) White ischemic retina with cherry red spot, (C) Flame-shaped hemorrhages throughout a quadrant, (D) AV crossing changes</p></div>
<div class="box box-green">Answer: (B) White ischemic retina with cherry red spot = CRAO. Artery = WHITE + embolus. Vein = BLOOD (hemorrhages) + thrombus. (A) disc edema can occur in both. (C) flame hemorrhages = vein occlusion. (D) AV crossing changes = arteriosclerosis / vein occlusion setup, not artery occlusion itself.</div>

<div class="q-block"><p>Q8. A 74-year-old has sudden painless vision loss OD. Fundus shows a diffusely white retina with a cherry red spot. What is the diagnosis, immediate management, and what age-related condition must be ruled out?</p></div>
<div class="box box-red">Answer: CRAO (Central Retinal Artery Occlusion) = stroke equivalent. Immediate ER referral; stroke workup within 24 hours. MUST rule out Giant Cell Arteritis (GCA) in patients &gt;50 years old. GCA can cause CRAO through vasculitic obliteration and requires urgent systemic steroids.</div>

<div class="q-block"><p>Q9. What BP defines hypertensive crisis, and what single clinical factor determines whether to call an ambulance?</p></div>
<div class="box box-green">Answer: Hypertensive crisis = BP &gt;180 systolic AND/OR ≥120 diastolic. The single most important factor for ambulance = SYMPTOMS OF ACUTE END-ORGAN DAMAGE (chest pain, shortness of breath, stroke-like symptoms). The number alone does not equal ambulance — symptoms do.</div>

<div class="q-block"><p>Q10. Should you avoid topical 2.5% phenylephrine in a patient with asthma? What drug class IS actually affected by a patient having asthma?</p></div>
<div class="box box-green">Answer: No — phenylephrine 2.5% is safe regardless of asthma. Asthma is NOT a contraindication to phenylephrine. The drug class affected by asthma = CARBONIC ANHYDRASE INHIBITORS (and some glaucoma medications). That is why clinics screen for asthma — not because of phenylephrine. Tropicamide is also unrelated (anticholinergic, different class).</div>

